issue_body:
Leafref paths in tree output don't follow the rules of [sec. 6.4.1](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6020#section-6.4.1) in RFC 6020. A simple example is this:
```
$ cat a.yang
module a {
  namespace "http://example.com/a";
  prefix a;

  container top {
    leaf foo {
      type empty;
    }
  }
}

$ cat b.yang
module b {
  namespace "http://example.com/b";
  prefix b;

  import a {
    prefix a;
  }

  leaf bar {
    type leafref {
      path "/a:top/a:foo";
    }
  }
}

$ pyang -f tree a.yang b.yang 
module: a
   +--rw top
      +--rw foo?   empty
module: b
   +--rw bar?   -> /a:top/foo
```

The leafref path should be `/a:top/a:foo` because the node `foo` is in a different namespace than the context node `bar`.

In the restriction of the ``foo`` type below, only the first character is parsed as the bit value:
```
$ cat -n bits.yang 
     1	module bits {
     2	  yang-version 1.1;
     3	  namespace "http://example.com/bits";
     4	  prefix b;
     5	
     6	  typedef foo {
     7	    type bits {
     8	      bit un;
     9	      bit dos;
    10	      bit tres;
    11	    }
    12	  }
    13	
    14	  leaf bar {
    15	    type foo {
    16	      bit un;
    17	      bit dos;
    18	    }
    19	  }
    20	}
$ pyang bits.yang 
bits.yang:16: error: the value "u" does not match its base type at bits.yang:6 - bit not defined
bits.yang:17: error: the value "d" does not match its base type at bits.yang:6 - bit not defined
```

It doesn't help if the arguments of the **bit** statements are quoted.

