According to the [API section](http://django-rest-framework-json-api.readthedocs.io/en/stable/api.html#rest-framework-json-api-renderers-jsonrenderer) of the documentation, "The `JSONRenderer` exposes a number of methods that you may override if you need highly custom rendering control." However, many of these methods are actually static and there are hardcoded calls to them in the code, making them unoverridable. For example:

```python
@staticmethod
def extract_relationships(fields, resource, resource_instance):
    # Avoid circular deps
    from rest_framework_json_api.relations import ResourceRelatedField
    # ...

@staticmethod
def build_json_resource_obj(fields, resource, resource_instance, resource_name):
    # ...
    relationships = JSONRenderer.extract_relationships(fields, resource, resource_instance)
```

Shouldn't these be classmethods instead?

I believe I've run into a bug in the configuration of related resource links. I think the issue starts here:

[rest_framework_json_api/relations.py#L101](https://github.com/django-json-api/django-rest-framework-json-api/blob/79b7c79f0c19fdda77dfc62e2ad58cedaad73033/rest_framework_json_api/relations.py#L101)

The `related_kwargs` dict is not actually configurable. The `related_link_lookup_field` is only used to access `kwargs`, which, because `get_links` [is not called with any kwargs](https://github.com/django-json-api/django-rest-framework-json-api/blob/79b7c79f0c19fdda77dfc62e2ad58cedaad73033/rest_framework_json_api/renderers.py#L160), has a kwarg `lookup_field` and is defaulted to "pk". It is rarely, if ever, that the child's lookup field is the parent's primary key, therein lies the problem. Here is an example of the **incorrect** output:

``` json
{
  "data": {
    "id": 241,
    "relationships": {
      "previous-shipment": {
        "data": {
          "type": "shipment",
          "id": "1439417"
        },
        "links": {
          "self": "http://localhost:8000/api/account/241/relationships/previous_shipment",
          "related": "http://localhost:8000/api/shipment/241/"
        }
      }
    },
    "type": "account"
  }
}
```

You'll notice that the related link _should_ be http://localhost:8000/api/shipment/1439417

**Possible solution**

I'll happily make a PR for this, but it's confusing enough that I want to make sure I'm on the right track.

My guess is that the `related_kwargs` is just getting set wrong. The assignment seems to be a reflection of the assignment on [L95](https://github.com/django-json-api/django-rest-framework-json-api/blob/79b7c79f0c19fdda77dfc62e2ad58cedaad73033/rest_framework_json_api/relations.py#L95). If that is the case, I think the code is just a bit off (this was tested and works):

``` py
related_kwargs = {self.related_link_url_kwarg: getattr(obj, self.related_link_lookup_field) if obj else kwargs[self.related_link_lookup_field]}
```

From [source][1]

```python
    def subscribe(self, subscription, callback=None, flow_control=()):
        ...
        if callable(callback):
            subscr.open(callback)
```

Instead it should be something like:

```python
if callback is not None:
    if callable(callback):
        subscr.open(callback)
    else:
        raise TypeError('Hey man, that is not, like, callable, man.')
```

[1]: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/blob/cc7da65b4a31d7a33055afe0bd6dc9855c3d6493/pubsub/google/cloud/pubsub_v1/subscriber/client.py#L130-L131
